data.title: Tuesday Trenches: The Justice League
data.meta_description: I’ve been wanting to do this for a long time.
data.text:
I know. I know. There’s stuff to talk about.

I’ve been wanting to do this for a long time, though, and this is my space.

DC is far superior to Marvel.

No, not the movies (I’m not a lunatic), but the characters, stories, comics, all of it. It’s better.

Marvel, specifically The Avengers, is all about how extraordinary people (minus Thor, of course) are capable of great, god-like feats. The Justice League are gods among men (minus Batman), who are just trying to be normal, but can’t. The heroes are more compelling, the villains are a thousand times better and the stories are far superior.

So, now that we’ve established DC is superior to Marvel, and that, like two members of the Justice League would wipe the floor with the entire cast of the Avengers, we’re going to pick which Cincinnati Bengals players correspond with which members of The Justice League.

We’ll get to the football stuff after.

Superman: Joe Burrow

Was this ever a question? Joe Burrow is the Man of Steel. He’s the leader of the team. He’s the top dog. With him, the sky’s the limit. Without him, the Bengals have to get creative, just like the JL.

With Burrow, there’s nobody the Bengals can’t go toe-to-toe with. Without him, the team is severely limited. That’s the only position where a backup just won’t do.

Batman: Sam Hubbard

Here’s the thing with Batman. He’s not stronger than anybody. He’s not faster than anybody. However, he’s smarter and more prepared than anyone, which is why Superman considers Batman to be the most dangerous man in the world. Sam Hubbard isn’t the best edge rusher on the team. He’s not the best run-stuffing player on the team either.

But everything Sam Hubbard does, he does with intelligence, skill, preparation and pure willpower. Just like Batman, he may be outmatched, but he won’t lose. How many times have we seen Hubbard take down a quarterback in the backfield who was a better athlete than him?

The Dark Knight does the same thing.

Plus, look at Hubbard’s face. He has the potential to have a great brooding look as he stands on top of Carew Tower looking down at Paycor.

Wonder Woman: Vonn Bell

Before you laugh, one must understand Wonder Woman is absolutely one of the most powerful characters in DC. She, Batman and Superman make up the “Big Three,” and she absolutely embodies the qualities of justice, strength and combat ability.

We missed Bell’s presence on the defense in 2023. The season was lost with Burrow’s injury, but the loss of Bell’s (and Jessie Bates’) ability to communicate with the rest of the secondary was pivotal in missing the postseason.

Bell is back, and his ability to lead, both vocally and physically, on the field will be extremely helpful against a Murderer’s Row of quarterbacks looking to win the Super Bowl.

This isn’t an insult. It’s a compliment of the highest order.

The Flash: Chase Brown

This was going to be Ja’Marr, but then Brown ran faster than everyone in the league other than DK Metcalf in 2023, hitting 22.03 miles per hour in Week 14 on his way to a 54-yard receiving touchdown. Chase hit 21.54 MPH in 2023.

The Flash, a master of the Speedforce, is beyond fast. Not only can he travel at ridiculous speeds, he can travel fast enough to go through time. He can vibrate his body fast enough to travel through solid objects. Fast doesn’t really cut it.

The Bengals have a lot of team speed, but Brown may be the fastest on the offense. He’s up for a large increase in playing time his sophomore season, and hopefully, he’ll tear up the field, leaving opposing defenders in his dust on his way to the end zone multiple times in 2024.

Cyborg: Ja’Marr Chase

What do you need Cyborg to do? Do you need him to fight? He can definitely do that, and do it well. Need him to fly? He can do that. Need him to do some crazy computer stuff? He can do that too.

What do you need Cyborg to do? He can do it.

What do the Bengals need Ja’Marr Chase to do? He can do it. When Chase has the ball in his hands, he’s a threat. He can do it all. He can be a deep threat, where he can beat any defense over the top. He can be a possession receiver, gaining the tough yards over the middle. He can take the ball out of the backfield. He can do it all.

Ja’Marr Chase is a Swiss army knife of a wide receiver. Just like Cyborg, he can do almost anything.

Green Lantern: Tee Higgins

The Green Lantern ring gives the wearer the power to conjure anything. The ring's powers are only limited by the wearer’s imagination and willpower. He can fly, he’s strong, he’s a leader and he uses his power, and his Power Ring, to make the world a safer and better place.

Tee Higgins is strong, he can fly (figuratively), he’s a leader and he’s one of the best 50/50 ball receivers in the league. What does it take other than skill, insane physical ability and strength to catch a 50/50 ball?

Willpower.

You just have to want it more than the other guy.

Higgins has it in spades.

If this isn’t willpower, I don’t know what is.

Aquaman: Logan Wilson

It’s no secret Aquaman is incredibly powerful. He’s a crazy-level superhuman on land, but he’s a god in the sea. He commands legions of underwater predators, as well as demands the respect of his peers and is feared by his enemies. Aquaman is no joke, and he can wreck shop with the best of them.

Wilson is among the best linebackers in the division and across the league. He’s a capable run defender, sure, but where he shines is in pass coverage. Just like Aquaman in the sea, when Wilson drops back into coverage, he’s a whole other animal. He leads all NFL linebackers with 11 interceptions since he entered the league in 2020. Quarterbacks have to know where he is, which always tends to be the right place at the right time.

Shazam: Amarius Mims

Billy Batson is a 14-year-old kid from Philly, but after he was given magic powers from ancient gods, he can transform into Captain Marvel, or Shazam, when he says the word “Shazam.”

Yeah, I think it’s dumb too, but he’s insanely powerful. He has lightning abilities, super strength and he can fly.

Do you know who else is young and has some crazy strength?

Amarius Mims is only 21 years old, and while that’s not 14, it also isn’t very old either. Mims is a rookie, but, from the limited amount we’ve seen, and from what we’ve heard, he has the potential to be a great right tackle, and a bookend tackle for Joe Burrow once he takes over.

Martian Manhunter: Mike Hilton

Not as widely known as his counterparts, J’onn J’onzz hales from the planet Mars but came to Earth to help the Justice League and fight crime. He has incredible strength, and even once helped Superman and Wonder Woman move Earth out of its orbit for a short period of time. What he’s most known for, though, is his ability to shapeshift, read minds and pass through solid objects.

Mike Hilton is probably the best “in the box” corner in the NFL. Don’t get me wrong though: he’s solid in pass coverage, but he makes his money pretending to be a linebacker. He enables the Bengals to defend against the run with one less linebacker on the field, making the defense more versatile overall.

This isn’t a normal cornerback thing. This is a cornerback who can shapeshift into a linebacker.

Also, Martian Manhunter’s weakness is being set on fire. I’m assuming the same goes for Hilton.

Green Arrow: Evan McPherson:

Olliver Queen, much like his Marvel counterpart, is a master with a bow and arrow. He’s just much better. One time, after losing an arm, he shot a Kryptonite arrow at Superman’s head and still had perfect aim. With one arm. How did he do that? He’s Green Arrow.

Do you know who else is deadly accurate? McPherson, or Money Mac, or whatever we want to call him. How accurate is he? PFF said he was the fourth-best kicker in the NFL in 2023, and he’s likely to get a big payday soon, as he’s entering the last year of his contract and is set to become an unrestricted free agent after the coming season.

That’s about all I got. If we go any further we’re going to get into Zatanna, Plastic Man, Dr. Fate and some of the other lesser-known heroes, and if I haven’t lost you yet, I’ll definitely lose you then.

So, some football:

I’m excited to see Trent Brown in action. We’ve seen some of what Mims can do, and there’s enough to be excited about, but I still think he’s got a thing or two to learn. I’m glad Mims has some experience. It could come in handy before the season is over, but I’m excited to see Brown in action.

The Bengals starters, including Joe Burrow, are going to be taking some snaps in the team’s first preseason game against the Bucs on Saturday evening. This is a major departure from what Zac Taylor has done in the past. We typically don’t get to see the starters until Week 1, and sometimes it takes a little while to knock the rust off. Considering the Chiefs are waiting for the Bengals in Week 2, starting slow would be bad.

I’m very anxious to see what new offensive coordinator Dan Pitcher has in store for the new backfield. Joe Mixon is gone, and now Chase Brown and Zack Moss will be the two primary backs to replace him. Who will get the majority of the carries? Will the Bengals ride the hot hand? Will Trayveon Williams be involved more? Who is Chris Evans?

I don’t know for sure, and I don’t have any inside knowledge, but I do believe the Bengals extend Chase before Week 1. They know how important he is, not only to the offense, but to Burrow. They didn’t extend Higgins because they wanted to extend Chase. I think it’ll happen soon.

The NFL Top 100 list was completely bonkers. Not only were Ja’Marr Chase and Joe Burrow criminally low, but Patrick Mahomes wasn’t even No. 1. I mean, I agree Tyreek Hill is an excellent wide receiver, but to say he’s better than Patrick Mahomes? Pure nonsense. I will be much less invested moving forward.

The WR3 battle isn’t really shaping up the way I thought it would. I expected one wide receiver to stand out above the rest and take the mantle of WR3 for himself, but I don’t know if that’s going to happen. By all accounts, Charlie Jones, Andrei Iosivas, Trenton Irwin, and others are having solid camps. I could see the situation dictating who is WR3 on the field at any moment. We’ll see.

I expect the defense to take some major strides in 2024. Vonn Bell is back and the team also signed Geno Stone. They play against one of the best in the business in practice, which should make things easier for them in a game. We’ll get our first look on Saturday!

Relevant Song Lyrics:

Where have all the good men gone

And where are all the gods?

Where’s the streetwise Hercules

To fight the rising odds?

Isn’t there a white knight upon a fiery steed?

Late at night, I toss and I turn

And I dream of what I need

Who Dey!
